===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|hamer|lang=enm}}, {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|hamor|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*hamaraz}} (compare {{etyl|fy|-}} {{term|hammer|lang=fy}}, {{etyl|nds|-}} {{term|Hamer|lang=nds}}, {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|hamer|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|Hammer|lang=de}}, {{etyl|da|-}} {{term|hammer|lang=da}}, {{etyl|sv|-}} {{term|hammare|lang=sv}}).
The Germanic ''*hamaraz'' "tool with a stone head" derives from a {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*h₂eḱmoros}} (compare Sanskrit {{term||tr=aśmará||stony|lang=sa}}), itself a derivation from {{m|ine-pro|*h₂éḱmō||stone}}.

For {{m|ine-pro|*h₂éḱmō||stone}}, compare {{etyl|lt|-}} {{term|akmuõ|lang=lt}}, {{etyl|ru|-}} {{term|камень|tr=kamen'|lang=ru}}, {{etyl|sh|-}} {{term|kamēn|lang=sh}}, {{etyl|sq|-}} {{term|kmesë|lang=sq}} 'sickle', {{etyl|grc|-}} {{term|ἄκμων|tr=akmōn||meteor rock, anvil|lang=grc}}, {{etyl|ae|-}} {{term|tr=asman|lang=ae}}, {{etyl|sa|-}} {{term|अश्मन्|tr=aśman|lang=sa|sc=Deva}}) (root {{m|ine-pro|*h₂eḱ-||sharp}}).

